\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1.1}{\ignorespaces (Image credit : Shep Doeleman) Cartoon image (left) combined with the ray-tracing of a thin accretion disc surrounding a BH, first calculated by \citet  {Luminet_1979}. The cartoon image shows that both the bottom and top of the far side of the accretion disc is lensed by the black hole and is superimposed on the image of the near side of the accretion disc. The dark area in the centre, known as the black hole shadow is the lensed image of the photon ring orbiting the BH. A measurement of its precise shape is a test of general relativity in the strong field regime. Note that the left-right asymmetry in the image is due to doppler boosting. \relax }}{6}{figure.caption.3}}
